knowledge_graph.title: Kewra
knowledge_graph.description: Kewra, keora or kewda is an essential oil distilled from the male flower of the fragrant screwpine. The plant is native to Tropical Asia, Southeast Asia and Australasia, and the oil is used as a flavoring agent throughout much of these regions.

related_questions.question: What is Kewda used for?
related_questions.snippet: The most well-known and celebrated aspect of the Kewda tree is its fragrant flowers. The essential oil extracted from these flowers is a beloved ingredient in the perfume industry. The sweet and exotic aroma is often used to add unique character to perfumes, attars, and essential oil blends.

list.title: Origin
list.snippet: The kewda plant is native to tropical and coastal areas of Southeast Asia, Australasia, and India.

list.title: Uses
list.snippet: Kewda oil is used as a flavoring agent and in perfumery. Kewda water is a byproduct of the distillation process and is used in cooking and skincare.

list.title: Properties
list.snippet: Kewda water is said to have a calming effect on the skin, help remove excess oil, and replenish moisture.

list.title: Taste
list.snippet: Kewda tastes similar to rose water but has a fruitier flavor.

list.title: Cultivation
list.snippet: The kewda plant can be propagated by seed or by cutting off offshoots that grow around the base of the trunk.

list.title: Geographical indications
list.snippet: The Government of India has registered the Ganjam Kewda as a Geographical Indication of Goods. The Ganjam district of Odisha supplies about 85-90% of India's kewda essence.
